<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="91" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bandala, Montoya &amp; M. Herrera" authorityYear="2021" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus veraecrucis" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by the basidiome colors, hymenophore smooth (or at times discontinuously rugulose) with pinkish tinges, and pileus surface with appressed fibrils. In some stage of development, it superficially might look like 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. flavolateritius" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="flavolateritius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. flavolateritius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; this latter, however, according to 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.7872/crym/v37.iss3.2016.367" author="Buyck, B" journalOrPublisher="Cryptogamie, Mycologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="367 - 389" refId="B12" refString="Buyck, B, Oraliaga, I, Justice, J, Lewis, D, Roody, W, Hofstetter, V, 2016a. The dilemma of species recognition in the field when sequences data are not in phase with phenotypic variability. Cryptogamie, Mycologie 37 (3): 367 - 389, DOI: https://doi.org/10.7872/crym/v37.iss3.2016.367" title="The dilemma of species recognition in the field when sequences data are not in phase with phenotypic variability." url="https://doi.org/10.7872/crym/v37.iss3.2016.367" volume="37" year="2016 a">Buyck et al. (2016a)</bibRefCitation>
exhibits bright yellow colors on pileus, the hymenophore is composed of radially oriented, low anastomosing veins,
<normalizedToken originalValue="“…">&quot;...</normalizedToken>
locally almost smooth
<normalizedToken originalValue="…”">...&quot;</normalizedToken>
, paler stipe (yellow to off-white), narrowly ellipsoid, somewhat phaseoliform basidiospores (7.1-) 7.2-7.88-8.5 (-10.0) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4.0-) 4.2- 4.71-5.2 (-5.8) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, Q = (1.4-) 1.5-1.69-1.8 (-2.1) and pileipellis terminal hyphae often rather short, clavulate or apically slightly inflated, rarely ellipsoid, mostly 20-50 (-70) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
long, sometimes more or less wavy-undulate in outline.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
In our phylogenetic analysis, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. veraecrucis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is related also with 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lateritius" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="lateritius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. lateritius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This latter species exhibits pale to deep yellow or even apricot orange (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/10-261" author="Buyck, B" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="1037 - 1046" refId="B10" refString="Buyck, B, Cruaud, C, Couloux, A, Hofstetter, V, 2011. Cantharellus texensis sp. nov. from Texas, a Southern lookalike of C. cinnabarinus revealed by tef-1 sequence data. Mycologia 103 (5): 1037 - 1046, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/10-261" title="Cantharellus texensis sp. nov. from Texas, a Southern lookalike of C. cinnabarinus revealed by tef- 1 sequence data." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/10-261" volume="103" year="2011">Buyck et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
) or bright orange or slightly pinkish orange colors (
<bibRefCitation author="Petersen, RH" journalOrPublisher="Sydowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="198 - 208" refId="B46" refString="Petersen, RH, 1979. Notes on cantharelloid fungi X. Cantharellus confluens and C. lateritius, Craterellus odoratus and C. aureus. Sydowia 32: 198 - 208" title="Notes on cantharelloid fungi X. Cantharellus confluens and C. lateritius, Craterellus odoratus and C. aureus." volume="32" year="1979">Petersen 1979</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/10-261" author="Buyck, B" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="1037 - 1046" refId="B10" refString="Buyck, B, Cruaud, C, Couloux, A, Hofstetter, V, 2011. Cantharellus texensis sp. nov. from Texas, a Southern lookalike of C. cinnabarinus revealed by tef-1 sequence data. Mycologia 103 (5): 1037 - 1046, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/10-261" title="Cantharellus texensis sp. nov. from Texas, a Southern lookalike of C. cinnabarinus revealed by tef- 1 sequence data." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/10-261" volume="103" year="2011">Buyck et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
with their field experience also cited that 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lateritius" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="lateritius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. lateritius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="“…">&quot;...</normalizedToken>
has an often excentrical, sometimes laterally compressed, short to long, more or less yellow stipe that can remain white at the base but is concolorous with the cap higher up, and it has an almost smooth to clearly veined often slightly pinkish tinted hymenophore (the senior author has never seen absolutely smooth specimens)...&quot;. Based on our revision of the epitype of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. lateritius" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="lateritius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. lateritius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Buyck 07.025 kept at PC, designated by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-011-0095-z" author="Buyck, B" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="35 - 46" refId="B9" refString="Buyck, B, Hofstetter, V, 2011. The contribution of tef-1 sequences to species delimitation in the Cantharellus cibarius complex in the southeastern USA. Fungal Diversity 49 (1): 35 - 46, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-011-0095-z" title="The contribution of tef- 1 sequences to species delimitation in the Cantharellus cibarius complex in the southeastern USA." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-011-0095-z" volume="49" year="2011">Buyck and Hofstetter 2011</bibRefCitation>
), it microscopically differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. veraecrucis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the basidiospores shape (ellipsoid to slightly phaseoliform) and the terminal hyphae of the pileipellis, which are (19-) 21-60 (-70) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-11 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, cylindrical to subclavate, tending to be wider than those of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. veraecrucis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Terminal elements of the pileipellis of Cantharellus species a, b C. lateritius (a Buyck 05.058 b Buyck 07.025 epitype) c C. veraecrucis (Bandala 4505, holotype). Scale bar: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.80.61443.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545055" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
The Asian 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus hiananensis" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="hiananensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus hiananensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
N.K. Zeng, Zhi Q. Liang &amp; S. Jiang, appears related also to 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. veraecrucis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but according to data by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.myc.2017.06.004" author="An, D-Y" journalOrPublisher="Mycoscience" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="438 - 444" refId="B1" refString="An, D-Y, Liang, Z-Q, Jiang, S, Su, M-S, Zeng, N-K, 2017. Cantharellus hiananensis, a new species with a smooth hymenophore from tropical China. Mycoscience 58: 438 - 444, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.myc.2017.06.004" title="Cantharellus hiananensis, a new species with a smooth hymenophore from tropical China." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.myc.2017.06.004" volume="58" year="2017">An et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
, it differs from the Mexican species by its smaller basidiome size (pileus 25-55 mm diam., stipe 30-55 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-10 mm), paler hymenophore (cream to yellowish white), stipe usually hollow covered with tiny, yellow to pale yellowish brown scales, smaller, subcylindrical basidiospores [6-7.09-8 (-9) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4-) 4.5-4.84-5 (-5.5) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
], and smaller basidia (50-70 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7-10 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
), (4-) 5 (-6) -spored and pileipellis terminal hyphae 23-82 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-8 mm, narrowly clavate or subcylindrical, sometimes subfusiform, with obtuse apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="91">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bandala, Montoya &amp; M. Herrera" authorityYear="2021" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Cantharellaceae" genus="Cantharellus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cantharellus veraecrucis" order="Cantharellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">Cantharellus veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
represents a wild edible mushroom that is harvested for consumption and commercialization during the rainy season, in the study site and surroundings; it is known as &quot;Oak mushroom&quot;. After our systematic multiyear sampling of basidiomes in the forests studied, we could observe that 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. veraecrucis" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="veraecrucis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. veraecrucis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a frequent chanterelle, and shares the same habit preferences as 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. violaceovinosus" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" rank="species" species="violaceovinosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="91">C. violaceovinosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, recently described from the same region (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.32.22838" author="Herrera, M" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="91" pagination="91 - 109" refId="B29" refString="Herrera, M, Bandala, VM, Montoya, L, 2018. Cantharellus violaceovinosus, a new species from tropical Quercus forests in eastern Mexico. MycoKeys 32: 91 - 109, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.32.22838" title="Cantharellus violaceovinosus, a new species from tropical Quercus forests in eastern Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.32.22838" volume="32" year="2018">Herrera et al. 2018</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
